title: For Sale:  SIG 226, 229 FT
postcontent:
For trade I have a P226 and a P229 both with the DA/SA action. The 226 is chambered in 9mm. The bore is shiny and clean with good rifling. The finish is in very good condition and mechanically it is perfect. This is the classic 226 frame with no rail stamped made in Germany. 

Since acquiring the P226 I've installed the factory SIG short reset trigger (SRT), and the updated hammer spring strut and spring assembly. I also installed an 18lb main spring. I haven't had any issues with light primer strikes and the trigger pull is phenomenal. Getting redundant, but I also updated the trigger bar spring to the new style. This required new grips and I installed hogue finger groove grips. They are awesome for my hands, but if you have smaller hands you will want to get thinner grips.  It has factory battle sights (not night sights). I cannot recall the terminology for the type of sights, but it has a single bar in the middle of the rear sight. 

I've completely stripped this firearm multiple times to thoroughly clean the frame and all of the internal components. I polished the feed ramp on the barrel to smooth out feeding. The only thing I would do to this 226 to make it absolutely PERFECT is install a nicer set of sights.

Included with the P226 will be 2 15rd SIG magazines, and 3 18rd MecGar magazines. MecGar is a factory magazine supplier for SIG and they are arguably better quality than the original 15 rounders.

The second firearm for trade is a P229. This handgun will include barrels chambered in both 40SW and .357SIG. Both bores are bright and clean with good rifling. I've never fired a round through the .357SIG barrel but it does appear used. This SIG is also a classic frame design with no rail. The finish on this pistol is also very good.

The P229 has not received any of the updates that the P226 has, but I'd be happy to help a buyer complete the updates.

With the P229 5 magazines will be included. 1 SIG 10rd mag, 1 SIG 12rd mag, and 3 15rd MecGar magazines.

As far as trades go I'd be interested in hearing what you have to offer. I may also consider cash sales.

I have ammo in both 9mm and 40SW that I might be willing to part with for the right deal.

Make an offer!

FOID Absolutely required.

Call or Text - Two 1 Seven - 7 Two 5 - One 6 Eight 2

Arsenal Makarov NEVER FIRED! Owned this since I bought it and never fired it! Had it cleaned twice by US Veteran with vast knowledge of firearms and a unique collection. 
9x18 9mm

2 FULL BOXES OF AMMO INCLUDED!

(1) Eight round magazine cleaning rod, manual

During the Second World War and the early Cold War, the 7.62×25mm Tokarev was the standard automatic pistol round for the Soviet Union and its satellites in Eastern Europe. This ammunition is still in use by many of these countries today. During the war the Red army had found a few shortcomings of its 7.62mm TT-33 pistol, one of which was a tendency to inadvertently drop its magazine while in operation. The army wanted something that was lighter, with a heel release instead of a button and different ammunition. A direct blowback design was chosen for the pistol's operation, since it would be quick and cheap to manufacture, as well as accurate, due to the fixed barrel design allowed by direct blowback operation.

The 9×18mm Makarov round was designed by B.V. Semin in 1946, and was intended to be a relatively powerful round with modest bolt thrust that could function safely in a simple or direct blowback pistol. It was based on the 9×18mm Ultra cartridge which was developed in 1936 by Gustav Genschow & Co. for the German Luftwaffe, as a more powerful alternative to the 9×17mm used in the Walther PP, also a simple blowback design pistol. Nikolay Fyodorovich Makarov went on to design the Makarov PM pistol around the 9×18mm Makarov round in 1948.

The Soviet military required that their ammunition should be incompatible with NATO firearms, so that in the event of armed conflict a foreign power would be unable to use captured Soviet ammunition supplies. 9×18mm Makarov ammunition uses a larger diameter bullet than other common 9  mm rounds. Indeed 9 mm Parabellum is 9.017 mm (0.355 inches), however 9×18mm Makarov rounds are loaded with bullets measuring 9.27 mm (0.365 in). After its introduction in 1951, the 9×18mm Makarov round spread throughout the militaries of Eastern Bloc nations.

title: Want To Buy:  Ruger Carbines .44 mag- BROKEN -tube fed, rotary fed, lever action or bolt
postcontent:
I am wanting to purchase a Ruger carbine .44 MAG for parts. A common problem with the Ruger carbine in tube fed, rotary magazine fed and lever action is the trigger guard assembly housing cracking at the front preventing the rifle from firing properly and safely. The trigger guard assembly housing is no longer available. (Ruger no longer sells the part, and the major parts houses do not have this part. If yours is broken you will not be able to find this part unless you buy another gun and take the assembly apart from another working gun. ( not an ecomomical way to try and fix a rifle.) Ruger recommends that if you find a part that you are going to take from another working gun that it needs to be fitted for the gun you're intending to fix by a qualified gunsmith. If yours is broken, you are left with a decorative 'non-– functional wall hanger' that you will not be able to use---------------- or you can sell the rifle as a parts rifle to me and use the cash that would not otherwise be available to you to help replace it with something that works.

If your trigger guard assembly is broken and you are interested in selling the rifle out for parts I would be interested in purchasing your rifle as a parts rifle. There are other parts, not the trigger guard assembly, that I need. If you observe that your trigger guard assembly is loose and wants to drop down partly out of the underside of the stock ahead of the trigger where the bullets feed into the rifle and the bolt action wants to lock up when this happens, then your trigger guard assembly is broken. You can verify this by contacting a gunsmith at your nearest Gander Mountain or by contacting Ruger Customer Service Department directly. (www.ruger.com or REDACTED).  They will verify that this part is no longer made, not readily available through gun parts supply stores and in a broken condition renders your rifle nonfunctional.

If you are located in Wisconsin we can likely arrange a safe mutually agreed upon in-person pickup point. If you are located out of the state of Wisconsin I would arrange to have you take your rifle to a gun shop within 30 min. of your home and upon transferring your rifle to the gun shop they will give you our agreed-upon cash price right at that time. You walk into the gun shop, hand the clerk the rifle, he pays you cash on the spot. The sale of your broken rifle is done at a safe location and you get paid right away. I would pay for the shipping cost and FFL transfer cost that would be required. In this way the rifle is also being transferred where I would be required to submit to a background check. This would ensure you that your rifle, even though broken, is being sold to someone who can legally own a firearm. If you have a Ruger carbine that you are interested in selling me please e-mail me or call me and I will share with you my contact information and work out a mutually agreed-upon purchase price and the name and address of the Gun Store nearest your home that will receive the rifle and pay you cash. The sale and transfer will take you the time it takes to drive to the gun shop, hand the clerk the rifle, receive your cash and drive home.

Thanks, Terry
REDACTED

If you're looking to buy it then you probably already know what it is and how hard they are to get. I'm asking $1700.00 OBO. She is BRAND NEW, NEVER FIRED! If interested send E-Mail. I can also send pictures. Still have original box, comes with a sling.  Mostly interested in cash really tired of trade offers for AR uppers worth at most $400.00
KSG
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
